Why is the Fed not doing its job?
STANFORD - The nomination of new Federal Reserve board members gives Americans - and the US Congress - an opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future path.
The obvious question, first to be asked, is how it was possible for the Fed to fail so badly in fulfilling its most important mandate - ensuring price stability.
That the Fed was completely caught off guard by the current inflation suggests a fundamental failure.
Institutional guilt research is certainly warranted now.
However, while monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
Another major question is therefore whether she will use her immense power to advance climate or social policy.
The Federal Reserve, for example, could deny loans to companies in the fossil energy sector, it could demand from banks that they only grant loans to companies with certified net-zero emissions plans, or direct lending towards desired alternatives.
In addition, it could decide to take up its regulatory activity explicitly in the name of equality or racial justice by requiring banks to specify where and to whom loans are given, who is hired and who is fired, and so on.
However, before we turn to the question of in which direction the Fed's regulation will or should move, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's severe failure.
In 2008 the US government made a far-reaching decision: Financial institutions could still primarily obtain the money for risky investments by selling short-term, debt-laden securities, but hordes of new regulatory agencies would from then on assess the risk sensitivity of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook large write-downs in bank balance sheets of the magnitude of the subprime mortgages.
However, in the ensuing ten years of more detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army has never once asked itself what actually happens in the event of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually entered in early 2020, the Fed then abandoned its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even greater scale.
In March, the commercial banks proved themselves unable to serve as an intermediary in the market for plain vanilla US government bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms were put on the long shelf.
A subsequent run occurred on money market funds.
The Fed rescued money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but it never came to that.
In addition, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported the prices of corporate bonds by essentially offering a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes".
In 2008, the Fed and the US Treasury had opposed the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial sector bailout package, the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
However, in 2020, among other things, an explicit floor for corporate bond prices was introduced through the "Powell put".
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks because the Fed and the US Treasury will simply extinguish every new fire with a new flood of money.
The problem lies, however, in the incentives that these strategies have created.
What's the point of going to the trouble of using spare cash or balance space for purchases at falling prices, to provide liquidity or treat a "forced sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will ultimately overshadow everyone and rake in the profits.
Why as a company would you still issue stocks when you can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state will support the debt or bail out the company, as was the case with the airlines.
Why as an investor hesitate when it comes to the purchase of dubious papers, if their value in bad times is guaranteed by a "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed?
No wonder that America is drowning in debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will bear the losses during the next downturn.
Student loans, government pensions, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for Uncle Sam's bailout to kick in.
However, each new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put more money into rescue efforts and people will not enjoy billions of newly printed money.
If the rescue packages everyone is expecting do not materialize, we will wake up to a major fire – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In the year 2008, regulatory authorities and lawmakers at least recognized the moral risk and were concerned that investors would reap profits in good times while taxpayers would absorb the losses in bad times.
In 2020, people were only boasting about the rescue efforts.
Exactly the Fed, which in 2008 also did not see the risks of subprime mortgages as little as the pandemic in 2020 and which now wants to conduct stress tests in terms of "climate risks", will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy or another disruptive event.
The Fed regulators don't even ask about those events.
And though letters and numbers combinations are produced under "interconnections", "strategic interactions", "network effects", and "credit cycles", it has not been successful in defining the "systemic" risk, aside from it becoming a catch-all term that grants all-encompassing power to regulatory authorities.
Regulatory bodies will never be able to foresee risks, accurately assess the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that immense debts can always be paid.
We have to turn the fundamental premise of a financial system on its head, in which the state always stands by debt mountains in bad times. And we have to do this before the fire department is put to the test.
Better regulation can bridge ideological divides.
The Left is right when it thinks that the large banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans little.
However, she is basing it on the wrong cause.
A massive effort to comply with regulations presents a significant barrier to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is senseless.
Regulations are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well designed.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a cushion against all shocks and does not require regulators to have telepathic abilities.
The Fed scandalously stopped companies in the area of narrow banking and payment service providers that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before committing to the rescue of the planet and the rectification of injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it performs its fundamental task of safeguarding the financial system.
